<DOC><DOCNO> AP881027-0046 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-88 0231EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     10-27 0603</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,400</SECOND><HEAD>Kahane Gets Court OK To Make U.S. Speaking Tour</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Brooklyn-born Rabbi Meir Kahane will be allowedto travel here from Israel for a speaking tour while he challenges agovernment finding that he had renounced his U.S. citizenship.   U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker on Wednesday ordered theState Department not to interfere with Kahane's plan to enter theUnited States early Thursday to begin a three-week speaking tour ata suburban Washington synagogue.   An attorney for Kahane, the founder of the militant JewishDefense League, argued in a hearing that Kahane only signed papersrenouncing his U.S. citizenship so he could retain his seat in theKnesset, the Israeli parliament.   Kahane sent a telegram to withdraw the renunciation after theIsraeli Supreme Court ruled his anti-Arab political party was racistand therefore ineligible to participate in the Nov. 1 parliamentaryelection.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Affirmative Action, South African Embargo Sought from Japanese</HEAD><TEXT>   Business</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A ``Model Japanese Code of Conduct'' issued bythe head of the Congressional Black Caucus asks Japanese business toexpand minority training, work and management opportunity in itsAmerican subsidiaries and to pull out of South Africa.   Rep. Mervyn Dymally, D-Calif., issued the code Wednesday after heheld hearings on what he called insensitivity in Japan to BlackAmericans.   Japan's ``extraordinary achievements'' in industry and technology``are tainted by a narrow, egocentrist view of the human family,''Dymally said in a preamble to the code.   Dymally said he sent the model code to the Japanese Embassy andreleased it ``in a quest to support the goal of racial equality andto insure the full dignity of all people of good will in America andJapan.''   The code asks that Japanese-owned firms in the United States``conform to the standard created by the most advanced U.S.corporations in promoting minority participation at all levels andin all aspects of industrial activity.''</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Government Sets Insurance Rates For Rocket Companies</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Department of Transportation is requiringthree U.S. rocket companies to obtain up to $80 million in propertydamage insurance coverage before using federal facilities forcommercial space launches.   The orders call for $80 million in insurance for Martin MariettaCorp. and for McDonnell Douglas Co., and $75 million for GeneralDynamics Inc. Martin Marietta makes the Titan launch rocket,McDonnell Douglas builds the Delta and Delta II, and GeneralDynamics makes the Atlas-Centaur.   Representatives of the rocket companies said Wednesday theinsurance demand was about what had been expected from the DOT.   Orders were expected today to cover any liability claims by thirdparties. Under terms of a commercial space transportation billpassed by Congress and now on President Reagan's desk, the thirdparty liability requirement could be set as high as $500 million foreach launch.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Warning Issued on Mobile Home Furnaces</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The manufacturer of Coleman mobile-homefurnaces will inspect the furnaces and offer a discount onreplacements because the furnaces could pose a danger ifinadequately maintained.   About 100,000 Model 8600 Solar Pak mobile home-furnaces areinvolved in the warning, the Consumer Product Safety Commissionreported Wednesday.   The commission said that both it and Coleman have receivedreports of carbon monoxide poisoning involving furnaces that haveeither been inadequately maintained or altered in some way.   The suspect furnaces can be identified by the name Coleman on thefront and the rating plate inside the furnace door, which will stateif it is a Coleman 8600 Solar Pak. Owners of the furnaces, and thoseuncertain about their units, can telephone Coleman at 1-800-232-SOLR.</TEXT></DOC>